ty politics?

Patrick Ruffini: What we saw in 2020 was a pretty surprising shift toward T=
rump among Latino and Asian voters, such that he almost won that election d=
espite being behind by eight points in the polls all year. He made some gai=
ns that really cemented his position as a potential candidate in 2024. If h=
e had underperformed by as much as the polls had expected, I don=E2=80=99t =
think he could have stuck around. The narrative that he didn=E2=80=99t actu=
ally lose was more plausible to his constituents because he did come very c=
lose in a lot of swing states.

He then absolutely upended the 2024
electoral landscape. Despite Democrats swapping in a woman of color who the=
oretically should=E2=80=99ve done better with these groups, she did roughly=
 how Joe Biden would=E2=80=99ve done because of how these voters were alrea=
dy moving, combined with the overall current political environment, which i=
s just a terrible environment for Democrats to be running in.

What did Trump do to win over these voters? Or is it just that they=E2=80=
=99re unhappy with the direction of the country right now?

What Trump didn=E2=80=99t do was say, I have a Latinos for Trump coalition,=
 I have an African Americans for Trump coalition. You see that on some sign=
s, but there was no formalized outreach like you would see in a traditional=
 Republican campaign. I think Trump placed these voters at the heart of his=
 appeal: infrequent voters who are working class, more diverse, and in fact=
 younger than the groups that he was aiming for previously. You also have h=
is appearances on
podcasts that were geared toward young Latino and Black men. According to e=
xit polls, Trump=E2=80=99s media strategy seemed to have hit the mark in te=
rms of getting these shifts among younger men, and younger non-white men in=
 particular=E2=80=94whereas Harris=E2=80=99s strategy of focusing on younge=
r women didn=E2=80=99t seem to bear much fruit.

You=E2=80=99ve been saying for a long time that the Democrats can=E2=80=99t=
 take the Hispanic community for granted. Obviously, it=E2=80=99s a fragmen=
ted group, but Hispanic voters seem to be swinging even more to the right a=
fter decades of gradually shifting in that direction. What are you seeing?

It was surprising that they swung even more to the right than the polls wer=
e expecting. We didn=E2=80=99t see a backlash to things like the Puerto Ric=
o joke at the Madison Square Garden rally or the =E2=80=9CBlack jobs=E2=80=
=9D comment. In fact, what you had was places like Osceola County, Florida,=
 and Allentown, Pennsylvania, each with a heavy Puerto Rican
population, swinging pretty heavily toward Trump. And this is a community t=
hat=E2=80=99s not known as Republican-leaning.

There was a lot of concern in the closing days of the election that Trump w=
as going to blow it with [Tony Hinchcliffe=E2=80=99s] Puerto Rico joke, and=
 Democrats expressed a lot of optimism about it spilling over with other Hi=
spanic voters. In fact, the opposite happened. And I think there=E2=80=99s =
a lesson in that. A lot of people just like to speak bluntly about things a=
nd think it=E2=80=99s okay to crack a joke every now and then. And I think =
the entire Democratic Party seems to have lost sight of that.

Is the divide between voters with college degrees and voters without colleg=
e degrees?

In 2016, you had a realignment among whites, but you still had a pretty sol=
id bloc voting for Democrats among African Americans and Latinos. That bega=
n to erode in 2020, and it continues to erode. I think it=E2=80=99s a long-=
term trend.

There=E2=80=99s a lot of research that the Democratic majority is held toge=
ther by social forces, like people going to Black churches, for instance. B=
ut people are doing those kinds of things less and less. They=E2=80=99re li=
ving in more integrated environments. You=E2=80=99re seeing intermarriage, =
you=E2=80=99re seeing suburbanization, and I think that all of these trends=
, over time, are going to make African Americans more like an 80-20 or 70-3=
0 Democrat-to-Republican group. Among Hispanics, we=E2=80=99re getting very=
 close to the point where they are probably going to be something close to =
a 50-50 group.

The Kids

Gen Z voters swung away from the Democratic Party. I can=E2=80=99t imagine =
that=E2=80=99s an educational divide. Is that mostly based on anxieties abo=
ut the economy?

These are the groups that have been hit hardest by inflation, particularly =
Gen Z and millennials, who were really devastated by the Great Recession. T=
hen you had Covid, and there=E2=80=99s a sense that they=E2=80=99re just in=
 a much more tenuous position economically. And then you add onto that infl=
ation and rising costs. And frankly, the cost of housing is an underplayed =
issue in this race because that=E2=80=99s not counted in the official infla=
tion statistics.

But young people haven=E2=80=99t really had the ability to buy homes, becau=
se mortgage interest rates were so sky-high. The cost of a starter mortgage=
 practically doubled under Joe Biden. I think that created a lot of
anxiety. Democrats used to be able to count on the youngest voters by about=
 20 points, and now, at least one of the exit polls has Democrats down to a=
 five-point lead with this group.

What will the Democratic coalition look like in the future?

Democrats have a choice to make. Certainly, they=E2=80=99re moving in the d=
irection of being a more college-educated party, and that reflects a lot of=
 the choices they made during this campaign. They pivoted at the very end b=
ack to this =E2=80=9Cdemocracy and abortion=E2=80=9D message. The abortion =
side of it seems to have been ineffective in mobilizing the groups they tho=
ught they=E2=80=99d mobilize. The problem was that they were losing a lot o=
f their voters on the fringes of the coalition=E2=80=94those voters were fo=
cused on the economy.

What will the Republican coalition look like?

It seems like we=E2=80=99re headed toward something more like a working-cla=
ss coalition that spans racial lines. And the real interesting
question is: What policy changes will come about because of this? You=E2=80=
=99ve already seen a change in emphasis, even in Trump=E2=80=99s first term=
, really setting aside the Paul Ryan-style budget cutting. Trump clearly ha=
s very little interest in that, but how far is that actually going to go in=
 a second term? If tariffs are going to move forward, what effect will that=
 have on the working class? That=E2=80=99s a question that=E2=80=99s very m=
uch up in the air right now for Republicans. Anyone who wins these election=
s has done so by doing better among non-college, late-deciding people who d=
on=E2=80=99t pay very close attention to politics.

The moments that Trump was able to create during the course of the campaign=
, from the trip to McDonald=E2=80=99s to the garbage truck thing=E2=80=94he=
 broke through and created images that people who aren=E2=80=99t paying att=
ention to politics 24/7 could really gravitate toward. So, it=E2=80=99s pos=
sible to galvanize people who haven=E2=80=99t voted before. Barack Obama
did it, and I think we have to give Trump credit because he was able to.

There=E2=80=99s only one Trump for Republicans, in the same way that Democr=
ats only have one Obama. Can this coalition stay together without him? Does=
 J.D. Vance keep it together?

That=E2=80=99s always the challenge. I think we=E2=80=99re trying to sidest=
ep the personality question because, like you said, Trump is unique. The th=
ings he was able to do during this campaign are not at all easily replicate=
d. And every candidate who comes forward in 2028=E2=80=94there will definit=
ely be a new candidate who comes forward=E2=80=94has to create their own co=
alition. They can=E2=80=99t just borrow the Trump coalition.

But I think the starting place for most Republicans will have to be populis=
m as opposed to a return to the old-school moderate establishment. That=E2=
=80=99s dead and buried at this point. J.D. Vance is probably one of the mo=
st successful examples I=E2=80=99ve seen of someone really adapting
Trump=E2=80=99s appeal, but doing it in a way that was super smooth and con=
nected with more moderate and suburban voters. I think we=E2=80=99re headed=
 to a more populist Republican Party, for better or worse.

