x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b><i>Tara Palmeri<=
/i>: I had you on almost exactly a year ago, and you called out that Trump =
was changing the Republican coalition. Can you talk a little about this pop=
ulist movement that is changing the parties and killing off identity politi=
cs?</b><br/><br/><i>Patrick Ruffini</i>: What we saw in 2020 was a pretty s=
urprising shift toward Trump among Latino and Asian voters, such that he al=
most won that election despite being behind by eight points in the polls al=
l year. He made some gains that really cemented his position as a potential=
 candidate in 2024. If he had underperformed by as much as the polls had ex=
pected, I don=E2=80=99t think he could have stuck around. The narrative tha=
t he didn=E2=80=99t actually lose was more plausible to his constituents be=
cause he did come very close in a lot of swing states. <br/><br/>He then ab=
solutely upended the 2024
electoral landscape. Despite Democrats swapping in a woman of color who the=
oretically should=E2=80=99ve done better with these groups, she did roughly=
 how Joe Biden would=E2=80=99ve done because of how these voters were alrea=
dy moving, combined with the overall current political environment, which i=
s just a terrible environment for Democrats to be running in.<br/><br/><b>W=
hat did Trump do to win over these voters? Or is it just that they=E2=80=99=
re unhappy with the direction of the country right now?</b><br/><br/>What T=
rump <i>didn=E2=80=99t</i> do was say, <i>I have a Latinos for Trump coalit=
ion</i>, <i>I have an African Americans for Trump coalition</i>. You see th=
at on some signs, but there was no formalized outreach like you would see i=
n a traditional Republican campaign. I think Trump placed these voters at t=
he heart of his appeal: infrequent voters who are working class, more diver=
se, and in fact younger than the groups that he was aiming for previously. =
You also have his appearances on
podcasts that were geared toward young Latino and Black men. According to e=
xit polls, Trump=E2=80=99s media strategy seemed to have hit the mark in te=
rms of getting these shifts among younger men, and younger non-white men in=
 particular=E2=80=94whereas <b>Harris</b>=E2=80=99s strategy of focusing on=
 younger women didn=E2=80=99t seem to bear much fruit.<br/><br/><b>You=E2=
=80=99ve been saying for a long time that the Democrats can=E2=80=99t take =
the Hispanic community for granted. Obviously, it=E2=80=99s a fragmented gr=
oup, but Hispanic voters seem to be swinging even more to the right after d=
ecades of gradually shifting in that direction. What are you seeing?</b><br=
/><br/>It was surprising that they swung even <i>more</i> to the right than=
 the polls were expecting. We didn=E2=80=99t see a backlash to things like =
the Puerto Rico joke at the Madison Square Garden rally or the =E2=80=9CBla=
ck jobs=E2=80=9D comment. In fact, what you had was places like Osceola Cou=
nty, Florida, and Allentown, Pennsylvania, each with a heavy Puerto Rican
population, swinging pretty heavily toward Trump. And this is a community t=
hat=E2=80=99s not known as Republican-leaning. <br/><br/>There was a lot of=
 concern in the closing days of the election that Trump was going to blow i=
t with [<b>Tony</b> <b>Hinchcliffe</b>=E2=80=99s] Puerto Rico joke, and Dem=
ocrats expressed a lot of optimism about it spilling over with other Hispan=
ic voters. In fact, the opposite happened. And I think there=E2=80=99s a le=
sson in that. A lot of people just like to speak bluntly about things and t=
hink it=E2=80=99s okay to crack a joke every now and then. And I think the =
entire Democratic Party seems to have lost sight of that.<br/><br/><b>Is th=
e divide between voters with college degrees and voters without college deg=
rees? </b><br/><br/>In 2016, you had a realignment among whites, but you st=
ill had a pretty solid bloc voting for Democrats among African Americans an=
d Latinos. That began to erode in 2020, and it continues to erode. I think =
it=E2=80=99s a long-term trend.
<br/><br/>There=E2=80=99s a lot of research that the Democratic majority is=
 held together by social forces, like people going to Black churches, for i=
nstance. But people are doing those kinds of things less and less. They=E2=
=80=99re living in more integrated environments. You=E2=80=99re seeing inte=
rmarriage, you=E2=80=99re seeing suburbanization, and I think that all of t=
hese trends, over time, are going to make African Americans more like an 80=
-20 or 70-30 Democrat-to-Republican group. Among Hispanics, we=E2=80=99re g=
etting very close to the point where they are probably going to be somethin=
g close to a 50-50 group. <br/></td>
