he problem was that they were losing a lot of their voters on the fringes o=
f the coalition=E2=80=94those voters were focused on the economy.<br/><br/>=
<b>What will the Republican coalition look like?</b><br/><br/>It seems like=
 we=E2=80=99re headed toward something more like a working-class coalition =
that spans racial lines. And the real interesting
question is: What policy changes will come about because of this? You=E2=80=
=99ve already seen a change in emphasis, even in Trump=E2=80=99s first term=
, really setting aside the <b>Paul Ryan</b>-style budget cutting. Trump cle=
arly has very little interest in that, but how far is that actually going t=
o go in a second term? If tariffs are going to move forward, what effect wi=
ll that have on the working class? That=E2=80=99s a question that=E2=80=99s=
 very much up in the air right now for Republicans. Anyone who wins these e=
lections has done so by doing better among non-college, late-deciding peopl=
e who don=E2=80=99t pay very close attention to politics. <br/><br/>The mom=
ents that Trump was able to create during the course of the campaign, from =
the trip to McDonald=E2=80=99s to the garbage truck thing=E2=80=94he broke =
through and created images that people who aren=E2=80=99t paying attention =
to politics 24/7 could really gravitate toward. So, it=E2=80=99s possible t=
o galvanize people who haven=E2=80=99t voted before. <b>Barack Obama</b>
did it, and I think we have to give Trump credit because he was able to.<br=
/><br/><b>There=E2=80=99s only one Trump for Republicans,</b> <b>in the sam=
e way that Democrats only have one Obama. Can this coalition stay together =
without him? Does J.D. Vance keep it together?</b><br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s =
always the challenge. I think we=E2=80=99re trying to sidestep the personal=
